  = section "Interrogative Forms" do
    %p The interrogative forms have for the most part already been discussed. The 'determiner' (“which? what?”) and 'quality' (“what kind of?”) are both handled by the adjectives #{t "ιή", "yē"} and #{t "έδα", "'eda"}, depending on the animacy of the noun being described. The 'person' (“who?”) and 'thing' (“what?”) fields are filled by the native pronouns #{t "μώ", "mā"} and #{t "μιή", "mie"}, which have cognates in most modern Semitic languages. The distinction between <i>mā</i> and <i>mie</i> is also a question of animacy.
    %p The interrogative of place (“where?”) is handled by the adverb #{t "ήκα", "'ēka"}, which etymologically consists of an adjective *ʔay- “which” (cf. Alashian #{t "ιή", "yē"}) and an adverb *kā “here”. #{t "Ήκα", "'ēka"} is used for location only; the interrogatives of direction (“whither? to where?”) and origin (“whence? from where?”) consist of prepositions plus <i>'ēka</i>: #{t "αδ ήκα", "'ad 'ēka"} (lit. “towards where?”) and #{t "βνε ήκα", "bne 'ēka"} (lit. “from where?”).
    %p The interrogative of time (“when?”) is #{t "μασή", "masē"}, another native form with cognates in a number of Semitic languages. The interrogative of amount (“how much? how many?”) is #{t "κάν", "kan"}, which behaves as a noun and will typically appear in the construct state accompanied by whatever is being quantified. The quantified noun always appears in the singular, regardless of logical number.
    %p The interrogative of way (“how?”) is #{t "βιμώ", "bimā"}, which consists of the clitic instrumental preposition #{t "βι-", "bi-"} “with” and the pronoun #{t "μώ", "mā"} “what?”. The interrogative of reason (“why?”) is simply #{t "μώ", "mā"}, having acquired an idiomatic adverbial function alongside its more typical pronominal one.
  
  = section "Proximal Forms" do
    %p Proximal forms have the basic meaning of “this”; that is, they reference something in close proximity to the speaker.
    %p The proximal determiner (“this”) is simply the quasi-adjective #{t "δή", "dē"}, which shows agreement in gender in number. Its pronominal equivalent, #{t "αδ̄δ̄εκώ", "'aḏḏekā"} and its other forms, fill the roles of the 'person' (“this person, this one”) and 'thing' (“this thing, this one”) categories. It also has two variants derived using prepositions, #{t "κααδ̄δ̄εκώ", "ka'aḏḏekā"} “such, like this” (and its feminine and plural counterparts) and #{t "βεαδ̄δ̄εκώ", "be'aḏḏekā"} “for this reason, therefore” (usually always masculine singular).
    %p The 'place' and 'direction' forms are primitive Semitic forms: #{t "ηών", "hān"} “here” and #{t "κυώ", "kuo"} “hither, to here”. The proximal adverb of origin, however, employs the preposition #{t "βνε", "bne"} “from”: #{t "βνε ηών", "bne hān"} “hence, from here”.
    %p The adverb #{t "αππών", "'əphān"} “now” is directly related to the noun #{t "πών", "pān"} “time, instance, occurrence” with what was once a definite article prefixed, though the connection between the two words is not readily apparent to most Alashian speakers.
    %p The proximal quantifier is #{t "δή πυώς", "dē puos"} “this amount [of]”, which consists of the demonstrative “this” plus the noun #{t "πυώς", "puos"} “amount, total”, borrowed from Greek #{t "πόσο", "póso"} “how much?”.
    %p The proximal adverb of way is #{t "κάκ", "kak"} “thus, this way”, which etymologically consists of the preposition <i>ka-</i> “like” and the locatival adverb *kā “here”.

  = section "Distal Forms" do
    %p The distal forms have a basic meaning of “that”, referencing something more distant from the speaker, whether physically or metaphorically. These closely parallel the proximal correlatives in their formation.
    %p As with the proximals, a number of these forms are directly derived from the demonstratives. The determiner #{t "ηού", "hū"} “that” is the distal demonstrative adjective, while the distal 'person' and 'thing' categories are filled by the distal pronouns such as #{t "ανού", "'anū"} “that person, that thing, that one”. The 'quality' and 'reason' categories are filled with pronouns augmented by clitic prepositions, namely #{t "καανού", "ka'anū"} “that kind of, like that” and #{t "βεανού", "be'anū"} “for that reason, therefore”.
    %p The distal adverb of place is #{t "θών", "ṯān"} “there”, a primitive Semitic form. The directional adverb is #{t "αδών", "'adān"} “thither, to there”, which historically consists of the preposition #{t "αδ", "'ad"} “toward” + #{t "θών", "ṯān"}. The adverb of origin is phrasal: #{t "βνε θών", "bne ṯān"} “thence, from there”.
    %p The distal adverb of time is #{t "πλέ", "ple"} “then”, a loanword from Cypriot Greek #{t "πιλαί", "pilé"} “already”, which in both languages also serves as a general marker of the perfect aspect.
    %p The distal quantifier is #{t "ηού πυώς", "hū puos"} “that amount, that much”, clearly built on the same model as #{t "δή πυώς", "dē puos"} “this amount, this much”. The adverb of way is #{t "κάκ", "kak"} “that way, like that, thus”, and is not distinguished from the proximal adverb of way.

