  = section "Indefinite Forms" do
    %p The indefinite forms mark an unknown or inspecific quantity or quality, either because the speaker does not know (e.g., “I saw something strange”) or simply is not revealing the information (e.g., “I saw someone you know”). Most Alashian indefinites involve the numeral #{t "(ά)ρ̄αδ", "('a)řad"} “one” in some form.
    %p The indefinite determiner “some, some kind of” is simply #{t "ρ̄άδ", "řad"}, the same as the adjectival form of “one”. Despite the illogic of it, #{t "ρ̄άδ", "řad"} may freely appear with plural endings if modifying a plural noun.
    %p The indefinite pronouns marking persons and things consist of an assimilated <i>řad</i> fused with the interrogative pronoun: #{t "ρ̄αμμιή", "řammie"} “someone”, #{t "ρ̄αμμώ", "řammā"} “something”. These decline in the same manner as the interrogative pronouns they were based on.
    %p The indefinite marker of quality is the adverb #{t "κάαρ̄αδ", "ka'ařad"}, which literally means “like one” or “like something”. Analogy likely played some role in its adoption.
    %p All of the indefinite locative and directional adverbs are phrasal. “Somewhere” is #{t "ηαλ ρ̄αδ μακκούν", "hal řad məkhūn"}, literally “at some place”. The directional “to somewhere” is #{t "ρ̄άδ μακκούνα", "řad məkhūna"}, featuring a frozen non-productive directional suffix *-a, eliminating the need for a preposition. “From somewhere” is, not surprisingly, #{t "βνε ρ̄άδ μακκούν", "bne řad məkhūn"}, literally “from some place”.
    %p Alashian has a number of indefinite adverbs of time. The one shown in the chart is #{t "πών", "pān"}, which means “once” or “sometime”, implying a single indefinite occurence sometime in the past. Indefinite future occurrences are generally handled with the idiom #{t "ιούν ηαλ αιιουνυώς̄", "yūn hal hayyūnuoš"}, literally “a day out of days”. Multiple indefinite occurrences (i.e., “sometimes”), whether past of future, are generally handled with #{t "πωνιήν", "pānien"}, the plural form of #{t "πών", "pān"}.
    %p The last few indefinites are loanwords. The indefinite quantifier “some, some amount” is #{t "ριδ̄μυώς", "riḏmuos"}, derived from Greek αριθμός “a number [of]”. The indefinite adverb of manner is #{t "βερ̄άδ μυώδ", "beřad muod"} “somehow, in some manner, by some means”, where #{t "μυώδ", "muod"} ultimately comes from French <i>mode</i>. The indefinite adverb of reason is #{t "βερ̄άδ λούχ", "beřad lūx"} “for some reason”, with #{t "λούχ", "lūx"} coming from Greek #{t "λόγος", "lógos"}.

  = section "Negative Forms" do
    %p Most of the negative correlatives feature a negative suffix *-ma or *-mā, which is related to the interrogative #{t "μώ", "mā"} “what?”; this is a fairly common Semitic construction, where sentences like “What is in my hand?” come to mean “There is nothing in my hand”. All of these negative forms must be accompanied by a negated verb (double negation).
    %p The *-ma/*-mā suffix is seen most clearly in the negative pronouns #{t "μιμμώ", "mimmā"} “nobody” and #{t "μαμμώ", "mammā"} “nothing”, both of which are non-declining. The negative determiner/adjective of quality, #{t "ήμα", "'ēma"} “no, no kind of” also uses it; note that this form acts as a prenominal particle or adjunct more than an adjective, since it also does not decline. The adverb of time, #{t "μαζμώ", "mazmā"} “never”, is derived from #{t "μασή", "masē"} “when?” + *-mā, but has undergone some vowel reduction and assimilation.
    %p All other negatives are phrasal and employ #{t "ήμα", "'ēma"}: #{t "ηαλ ήμα μακκούν", "hal 'ēma məkhūn"} “nowhere”, #{t "ήμα μακκούνα", "'ēma məkhūna"} “to nowhere”, #{t "βνε ήμα μακκούν", "bne 'ēma məkhūn"} “from nowhere”, #{t "ήμα πυώς", "'ēma puos"} “no amount of”, #{t "βεήμα μυώδ", "be'ēma muod"} “in no way”, #{t "βεήμα λούχ", "be'ēma lūx"} “for no reason”.

  = section "Universal Forms" do
    %p The universal correlatives all have the basic meaning of “all” or “every”. Many of these forms revolve around the adjective #{t "κάλ", "kal"} “all, every”.
    %p There are only two universal correlatives that are not phrasal. One is #{t "κάλ", "kal"}, which means “all” or “every” when used attributively or “everything” when used nominally; it also has a derived adjective #{t "καλεί", "kalī"} “each”. The other is #{t "παχεί", "paxī"} “always”, derived from Greek #{t "εποχή", "epoxí"} “period, age, epoch”.
    %p The following forms are phrasal: #{t "κάλ τείπ", "kal tīp"} “every kind of”, #{t "κάλ άρ̄αδ", "kal 'ařad"} “everyone, each”, #{t "ηαλ κάλ μακκούν", "hal kal məkhūn"} “everywhere”, #{t "καλ μακκούνα", "kal məkhūna"} “to everywhere”, #{t "βνε κάλ μακκούν", "bne kal məkhūn"} “from everywhere”, #{t "κάλ πυώς", "kal puos"} “every amount of”, #{t "βικάλ μυώδ", "bikal muod"} “in every way, by all means”, #{t "βικάλ λούχ", "bikal lūx"} “for every reason”.

