  = section "Indeterminate Forms" do
    %p The indeterminate forms have the basic meaning of “any”. They are completely identical to the negative forms; the two are distinguished only by the polarity of the main verb, with positive verbs giving indeterminate meaning and negative verbs giving negative meaning.

  = section "Alternative Forms" do
    %p The alternative correlatives mean “other” or “else”. There are two main stems at work: the native Semitic #{t "χάρ", "xar"} “other” and the Greek prefixial #{t "αλλι-", "'alli-"}, from Greek #{t "άλλος", "allós"} “other”.
    %p The alternative determiner is simply the adjective #{t "χάρ", "xar"} “other, another”. The qualitative alternative is the loaned Greek adjective #{t "αλλούν", "'allun"} “another kind of”.
    %p The pronouns feature the prefix <i>'alli-</i> attached to an interrogative base: #{t "αλλιμιή", "'allimie"} “someone else, another”, #{t "αλλιμώ", "'allimā"} “something else, another”. A similar form is seen in #{t "αλλιπαχεί", "'allipaxī"} “some other time”, though this is instead created from the base #{t "παχεί", "paxī"} “always”.
    %p All other forms are phrasal: #{t "ηαλ χάρ μακκούν", "hal xar məkhūn"} “somewhere else”, #{t "χάρ μακκούνα", "xar məkhūna"} “to somewhere else”, #{t "βνε χάρ μακκούν", "bne xar məkhūn"} “from somewhere else”, #{t "χάρ πυώς", "xar puos"} “some other amount”, #{t "βιχάρ λούχ", "bixar lūx"} “for some other reason”. The adverb of alternative method, #{t "βιχαρείς", "bixarīs"} “another way, differently” is also technically phrasal, but is formed from the noun #{t "χαρείς", "xarīs"} “otherness, difference”, a nominalized form of #{t "χάρ", "xar"}.

